===The Achemenid fleet===
[[File:Kybernis north BM B287.jpg|thumb|The [[Lycia]]n dynast [[Kybernis]] (520-480 BCE) led 50 Lycian ships in the Achaemenid fleet.]]
[[File:Meeting of the Ionian fleet and the Persian army.jpg|thumb|The Ionian fleet, here seen joining with Persian forces at the [[Bosphorus]]  in preparation of the [[European Scythian campaign of Darius I]] in 513 BC, was part of the Achaemenid fleet at Salamis. 19th century illustration.]]
According to Herodotus, the Persian fleet initially numbered 1,207 triremes.&lt;ref name = VII89&gt;Herodotus [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0126&amp;layout=&amp;loc=7.89.1 VII, 89]&lt;/ref&gt; However, by his reckoning they lost approximately a third of these ships in a storm off the coast of [[Magnesia (regional unit)|Magnesia]],&lt;ref&gt;Herodotus [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0126&amp;layout=&amp;loc=7.188 VII, 188]&lt;/ref&gt; 200 more in a storm off the coast of Euboea,&lt;ref name = VIII14&gt;Herodotus [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0126;query=chapter%3D%231317;layout=;loc=8.13.1 VIII, 14]&lt;/ref&gt; and at least 50 ships to Allied action at the Battle of Artemisium.&lt;ref name = VIII14/&gt;&lt;ref name = VIII11&gt;Herodotus [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0126;query=chapter%3D%231314;layout=;loc=8.10.1 VIII, 11]&lt;/ref&gt; Herodotus claims that these losses were replaced in full,&lt;ref name = VIII66&gt;Herodotus [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0126;query=chapter%3D%231372;layout=;loc=8.65.1 VIII, 60]&lt;/ref&gt; but only mentions 120 ships from the Greeks of Thrace and nearby islands as reinforcements.&lt;ref name = VII185&gt;Herodotus [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0126&amp;layout=&amp;loc=7.185.1 VII, 185]&lt;/ref&gt; [[Aeschylus]], who fought at Salamis, also claims that he faced 1,207 warships there, of which 207 were &quot;fast ships&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;Aeschylus, ''The Persians''&lt;/ref&gt; [[Diodorus Siculus|Diodorus]]&lt;ref&gt;Diodorus Siculus [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0084&amp;layout=&amp;loc=11.3 XI, 3]&lt;/ref&gt; and [[Lysias]]&lt;ref&gt;Lysias II, 27&lt;/ref&gt; independently claim there were 1,200 ships in the Persian fleet assembled at Doriskos in the spring of 480 BC. The number of 1,207 (for the outset only) is also given by [[Ephorus]],&lt;ref&gt;Ephorus, Universal History&lt;/ref&gt; while his teacher [[Isocrates]] claims there were 1,300 at Doriskos and 1,200  at Salamis.&lt;ref&gt;Isocrates, Oration VII, 49&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;Isocrates, Oration IV, 93&lt;/ref&gt;  Ctesias gives another number, 1,000 ships,&lt;ref name = ctes&gt;Ctesias, [https://www.livius.org/ct-cz/ctesias/photius_persica2.html Persica] (from Photius's Epitome)&lt;/ref&gt; while [[Plato]], speaking in general terms refers to 1,000 ships and more.&lt;ref&gt;Plato, ''Laws'' III, 699&lt;/ref&gt;

Herodotus gives a precise list of the ships of the various nations that composed the Achaemenid fleet:&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book |last1=Romm |first1=James |title=Histories |date=2014 |publisher=Hackett Publishing |isbn=9781624661150 |page=381 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JK7xAgAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA381 |language=en}}&lt;/ref&gt;

